The memory impairing side effects of Benzodiazepines, a.k.a. anti-anxiety medications, have long been studied within the research literature. This is especially true when considering the long-term use of these drugs. Here is a study testing these effects from kaggle.com. The experiment was conducted on two different drugs in comparison with a sugar pill as a placebo. Participants were all adult-aged, 25 years old or older, to ensure the study tested people with fully developed pre-frontal cortices, a brain region responsible for higher-level cognition and memory recall. This allows us to be confident that we used a normal sample to test for memory differences.

As an added feature, the experiment included the priming of either happy or sad memories before carrying out the rest of the experiment. There has been research showing the effects of both happy and sad memories in memory recall, with sad memories tending to produce more accurate accounts of information and happy memories tending to lead more to false memories afterwards. This has been partly explained by historical evolutionary needs. The priming was done 10 minutes prior to testing, and participants were tested every day for one week.

The three medications given were Alprazolam (Xanax), Triazolam (Halcion), and a sugar tablet as a placebo. Participants were further separated into 3 different dosage categories of the medication in their experimental conditions. These dosages ranged from 3 strength levels. Of the two anti-anxiety medications given, Alprazolam is typically prescribed for long-term use, whereas Triazolam is only meant for short-term use. 

In order to test the results for this dataset against the research literature, I measured the relationships between each of the three experimental groups, (the Happy or Sad memory experimental condition, the type of Drug used and dosage strength), all against the differences in test results before and after the drugs were given. 

Therefore, for this experiment we have 3 null hypotheses, each for the different experimental conditions within the data. They are that there is no relationship between priming happy or sad memories to individual memory recall, there is no relationship between anti-anxiety medication and individual memory recall, and that there is no relationship between severity of individual dosage strength of the medication on memory recall.

To conduct these tests, I used a chi-square analysis on each of the three pairs of variables within the dataset. In order for this to work, I had to re-purpose the individual memory test results given within the dataset into a categorical variable. I did this by changing up one of the columns in the dataset named 'Diff'. This column subtracted the test results prior to issuing the drugs from the test results after the drugs had been taken. I added an additional column into the dataset, where I separated the differences between the before and after memory scores that were 0 or negative into one category, and all positive differences between the test scores as another category. This way, the participants that were not affected or negatively affected by their experimental condition were given the value '0', and those that did better in memory recall after their experimental condition were given the value '1'. 

As an added bonus, I decided to test if age had any relationship with memory recall, outside of any of the other variables present. For this analysis, I just used a simple linear regression between age and the difference in memory recall scores. The null hypothesis for this, then, is that Ho $Î²_1$ = 0. 

One thing that does not seem clear in the experiment description is whether or not the memory tests given before and after each experimental condition were the same exact memory tests. It would be safe to assume that the tests were identical, since that would be the only way to get reliable measurements for improvements versus impairments in memory. If this is the case, then a limitation of this study would be the inability to completely account for natural improvements participants would recieve in their results from being re-tested on the same material. An increase, regardless of experimental condition, would then be expected. However, given the fact that there were still a substantial number of worse results after testing, attests to memory loss from drugs in it and of themselves. This was my rational for including scores that did not increase or decrease within the negative score condition. That way we could attempt to approximate a more accurate split between the two groups.

After performing the chi-square tests, we found that we could not reject the null hypothesis for the effects happy and sad memories have on memory recall. We recieved a p-value of about 0.89 which is greater than the 0.05 level. Therfore happy and sad memories do not seem to affect overall memory recall based off of these results.

When performing the chi-square on the drug and dosage strength conditions, we found a p-value of 0.038 and 0.043, respectively. Both of these are below our alpha level of 0.05, therefore we can reject the null hypotheses for both of these experimental conditions. We conclude that there is a relationship between anti-anxiety medicine use and memory as well as dosage strength and memory recall. Here is a graph of the three conditions below:

As you can see from the bar plots above, there is no visible difference in data amongst the happy and sad conditions. However with the graphs below. We start to see noticeable differences in the data. Interestingly enough when looking at the relationship between drug type and memory recall, there is only a difference between the Alprazolam condition and tests scores. Most of the memory impairments seem to be noticeable on this drug condition and none of the others. As a matter of fact, Triazolam is shown to have no more effects on memory recall than that of the placebo. This is interesting, considering the fact that Triazolam is only ever prescribed as a short-term medication as opposed to Alprazolam, which tends to be prescribed long-term more frequently. The memory impairing effects of anti-anxiety medication tend to be more pronounced when used long-term in the research literature, making these findings more relevant. 

When comparing the last plot on dosage strength and its relationship between drug conditions, we can see a gradual change in memory loss within the second and third strength conditions. These results are not surprising, and they reflect what we would expect to see with an increase in consumption of Benzodiazepines. Differences in effects are not detectable in the weakest of the three dosage amounts, however, suggesting that there is a certain threshold of medication needed before impairments in memory occur.

As a final part of our analysis, we conducted a linear regression on the age of participants and their memory scores. We failed to reject the null hypothesis when testing for both memory scores before and after drug administration, as well as the differences between the two scores at p-values of  0.355, 0.468 and 0.897, respectively. Therefore we can conclude that there is no relatioship between age and any of the memory test results.

With these results, we can begin to see at what point and what types of medications may cause impairments in individuals. Despite participants potentially being re-tested on the same material, a huge chunk of individuals still performed worse the second time testing. This suggests a strong effect on memory impairments, despite the study's potential limitations. Future research may want to further explore how longer-term dosages affect memory recall as opposed to short-term consumption. Happy and sad memories did not show any differences amongst the conditions and future research may want to explore the limits of emotional priming on memory recall. All in all, our results support most of the research literature, and we can conclude that there do exist differences in memory when consuming anti-anxiety medication.
